<h3>PI3K/AKT: The Master Growth Switch</h3>

<p>When IGF-1 LR3 docks with the IGF-1 receptor, it fires up the PI3K/AKT signaling cascade. This is the same pathway that mTOR sits on, and it's the primary driver of muscle protein synthesis.</p>

<p>AKT also blocks several pro-apoptotic signals, which means existing muscle fibers are protected from breakdown during hard training or caloric deficits. It's both a "build more" and "keep what you have" pathway.</p>

<h3>MAPK/ERK: Satellite Cell Activation</h3>

<p>The MAPK/ERK arm does something natural IGF-1 also does, but less effectively. It wakes up satellite cells, the dormant muscle stem cells that sit between muscle fibers waiting for a signal to divide.</p>

<p>Once activated, these satellite cells proliferate, differentiate into myoblasts, and fuse with existing fibers. This adds new myonuclei, which is the mechanism behind long-term muscle growth that persists even after you stop using the peptide.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Research Finding</div>
  <p>A 2010 study with resistance-trained men found those using IGF-1 LR3 gained <strong>9.1% more muscle mass</strong> than controls following identical training programs (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20150902/">Lee et al., 2010</a>).</p>
</div>

